    <article class="article">
      <div class="kicker">Stock in Focus</div>
      <h1>Cordel Group (CRDL)</h1>
      <p class="subhead">
        Rail technology / infrastructure software micro-cap combining capture hardware and AI-driven analytics to automate rail asset inspection and compliance workflows.
      </p>

      <div class="meta">
        <span class="pill primary">AIM</span>
        <span class="pill">Infrastructure AI</span>
        <span class="pill">DaaS / SaaS</span>
        <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        <span>Author: <strong>SmallcapsBigBags</strong></span>
        <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        <span>Published: <strong>27 Feb 2026</strong></span>
      </div>

      <div class="grid">
        <!-- Left: narrative intro -->
        <div class="card">
          <h2>What does the company do?</h2>
          <p>
            Cordel operates at the intersection of infrastructure and AI. The group provides rail inspection and analytics through a vertically integrated model:
            LiDAR and video capture hardware mounted on trains feeds Cordel‚Äôs proprietary software platform, and AI automates asset detection, clearance monitoring and regulatory workflows.
            Manual surveys are replaced with automated, repeatable data capture.
          </p>

          <p class="callout">
            <strong>Business model:</strong> hardware-enabled Data-as-a-Service. Initial deployments generate hardware and project revenue; over time the value shifts toward higher-quality recurring analytics subscriptions.
          </p>

          <p class="muted">
            Mental model: land the contract ‚Üí embed the hardware ‚Üí expand the data layer.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Right: facts -->
        <aside class="card" aria-label="Key facts">
          <h2>Key facts</h2>
          <table class="facts" role="table">
            <tr>
              <th>üè∑Ô∏è Ticker</th>
              <td><strong>CRDL</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>üí∞ Market cap</th>
              <td>¬£10.5m <span class="muted">(at 27.02.2026)</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>üìà Share price</th>
              <td>4.90p <span class="muted">(at 27.02.2026)</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>üìä 52-week range</th>
              <td>4.35p ‚Äì 8.13p</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>üè≠ Industry</th>
              <td>Rail technology / infrastructure software</td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </aside>
      </div>

      <section class="section">
        <h2>What is PTC Asset Connect?</h2>
        <p>
          PTC Asset Connect is the strategic development of the past year. Positive Train Control (PTC) is a mandated US rail safety system designed to automatically prevent collisions,
          derailments and incorrect switch movements.
        </p>
        <p>
          Running PTC creates a permanent compliance obligation: railroads must continuously audit their digital inventories of every trackside asset. That‚Äôs the workflow Cordel automates.
        </p>

        <div class="card" style="margin-top:12px;">
          <h2>What Cordel‚Äôs AI does</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Detect and classify assets from LiDAR and video datasets</li>
            <li>Geo-locate assets precisely</li>
            <li>Update compliance registers and associated workflows</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="muted">
            Cordel secured its first PTC contract before the formal July 2025 launch.
          </p>
          <p>
            In June 2025, a US Class 1 contract was structured as: <strong>US$3.7m</strong> base value over five years plus a <strong>US$3.8m</strong> contingent PTC SaaS component.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <h2>Strategic positioning ‚Äî US Class 1 penetration</h2>
        <p>
          At ~¬£5m annual revenue, Tier-1 customer upgrades can be material. Cordel now serves three of the seven North American Class 1 freight railroads, plus Amtrak, Genesee &amp; Wyoming and Network Rail.
        </p>

        <p class="callout">
          A third Class 1 PTC and clearances contract was announced in February, structured around a <strong>3,000-mile validation phase</strong>. Hardware is being installed on a geometry testing vehicle,
          with commissioning targeted for <strong>Q1 2026</strong>. Validation success could lead to a larger rollout.
        </p>

        <p class="muted">
          The contract appears to have progressed from a prior data-sharing relationship rather than a cold start, which may improve the probability of commercial expansion if commissioning and validation complete successfully.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <h2>The moat</h2>
        <p>
          This is not a ‚Äúblue-sky AI‚Äù story. It is embedded, mission-critical infrastructure. The moat is built on:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Proprietary capture hardware</li>
          <li>Rail-specific AI models</li>
          <li>The cloud-based Cordel Connect platform</li>
          <li>Tier-1 customers such as Amtrak, Genesee &amp; Wyoming and Network Rail</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <h2>Interim results / latest financials</h2>
        <p>
          Commercial traction is evident, but growth and timing are volatile due to procurement cycles and contract timing.
        </p>

        <div class="two-col">
          <div class="card">
            <h2>Reported</h2>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>FY24</strong> revenue: ¬£4.44m (+46%)</li>
              <li><strong>FY25</strong> revenue: ¬£4.79m (+8%) ¬∑ improved EBITDA ¬∑ closing cash: ¬£1.50m</li>
              <li><strong>H1 FY26</strong> revenue: ¬£1.73m (-24%) ¬∑ cash: ¬£1.02m</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="card">
            <h2>Interpretation</h2>
            <p>
              H1 FY26 showed a stall in growth. Management cited long procurement cycles and delayed purchase orders in the US and UK, with an expectation of H2 recovery.
            </p>
            <p class="muted">
              If H2 recovery fails to materialise, cash may become tight relative to operating needs.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <h2>Pipeline</h2>
        <p class="callout">
          <strong>Qualified pipeline</strong> grew <strong>133% YoY</strong> from <strong>¬£30m</strong> to <strong>¬£70m</strong>, spanning <strong>40+</strong> active projects across new and existing customers.
        </p>
        <p class="muted">
          Pipeline does not equal contracts, but relative to a ~¬£10m market cap it remains a notable indicator of potential opportunity.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <h2>Bull vs bear</h2>
        <div class="two-col">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="tag pos">Bull case</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Tier-1 customers:</strong> three of seven US Class 1 railroads is a meaningful endorsement.</li>
              <li><strong>Regulatory tailwinds:</strong> PTC compliance mandated in the US.</li>
              <li><strong>Operating leverage:</strong> at ~¬£5m revenue, incremental expansion can change the profit profile.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="card">
            <div class="tag neg">Bear case</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Lumpy revenue:</strong> long procurement cycles and budget timing reduce visibility.</li>
              <li><strong>Balance sheet sensitivity:</strong> ¬£1.02m cash (Dec 2025) provides limited buffer if conversion slips.</li>
              <li><strong>Rollout risk:</strong> validation must convert for PTC to scale.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Cordel presents an unusual combination for an ~¬£10m AIM micro-cap: international footprint, Tier-1 customers, and a tangible infrastructure AI use case.
        </p>
        <p>
          If PTC rolls out at scale, the business could evolve into a sticky, higher-margin data model. However, it remains small, revenue is lumpy, and cash sensitivity increases if H2 execution disappoints.
        </p>

        <div class="card" style="margin-top:12px;">
          <h2>Multi-bagger potential</h2>
          <div class="score">
            <div class="value">8/10</div>
            <div class="label">Tier-1 validation ¬∑ Regulatory driver ¬∑ Embedded DaaS upside ¬∑ ¬£10m market cap</div>
          </div>
          <p class="muted" style="margin-top:10px;">
            At this valuation, positive newsflow can re-rate quickly; equally, another soft period can shift focus to the balance sheet.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <h2>Trade plan</h2>
        <p class="muted">Share price as at 27.02.2026 (Source: Stockopedia).</p>

        <div class="two-col">
          <div class="card">
            <h2>Position</h2>
            <p>
              The share price sold off following H1 results and appears to have found support around ~4.5p.
              A small starter position was taken to monitor developments.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Purchased: <strong>20,000</strong> shares</li>
              <li>Price: <strong>4.9p</strong></li>
              <li>Notional: <strong>¬£980</strong></li>
              <li>Date: <strong>27.02.2026</strong></li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="card">
            <h2>Catalysts to monitor</h2>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Q1 2026:</strong> hardware commissioning on third Class 1 contract ‚Äî first data capture</li>
              <li><strong>By end Q3 FY26 (Mar 2026):</strong> management target to be ahead of FY25 revenue ‚Äî first H2 proof point</li>
              <li><strong>H2 FY26:</strong> PTC pipeline conversion from 40+ project funnel</li>
              <li><strong>FY26:</strong> consensus revenue ¬£6.2m ‚Äî meaningful re-rating if achieved</li>
            </ul>
